add("Online higher education shifts a substantial share of regulatory responsibility from the institution to the learner. In the absence of fixed timetables, physical co-presence, and the social scaffolding of the classroom, students must initiate, sustain, and adjust their own study behaviour with limited external structure. Under these conditions motivation—the set of psychological processes that govern the direction, intensity, and persistence of effort—becomes a decisive rather than peripheral determinant of success (Deci & Ryan, 2000; Ryan & Deci, 2000). Empirical work on distance environments shows that motivation in these settings is not a stable trait but is complex, multifaceted, and situation-dependent, fluctuating with task demands and contextual support (Hartnett et al., 2011). This autonomy-intensive character explains why two learners with comparable prior attainment can diverge sharply in outcomes: the heightened self-direction required online amplifies the behavioural consequences of motivational differences, making motivation a particularly powerful—yet, in most administrative datasets, unmeasured—lever for early prediction of failure and dropout.",
"Online higher education shifts much regulatory responsibility from institution to learner. Lacking fixed timetables, co-presence, and classroom scaffolding, students must initiate, sustain, and adjust their study with limited external structure. Under these conditions motivation—the processes governing the direction, intensity, and persistence of effort—becomes a decisive determinant of success (Deci & Ryan, 2000; Ryan & Deci, 2000), and in distance settings it is not a stable trait but complex, multifaceted, and situation-dependent, fluctuating with task demands and contextual support (Hartnett et al., 2011). This autonomy-intensive character explains why two learners of comparable prior attainment can diverge sharply: heightened self-direction amplifies the behavioural consequences of motivational differences, making motivation a powerful—yet, in most administrative datasets, unmeasured—lever for early prediction.")

add("The two theories are mutually reinforcing. SDT explains *why* certain study behaviours are energised and sustained from within, while EVT explains *which* tasks students choose to invest in and *how much* cost they will absorb. Together they predict that motivated learners will display engagement that is regular, exploratory, timely, and resilient—precisely the behavioural signatures the MPI seeks to capture.",
"The two theories are complementary: SDT explains *why* study behaviours are energised from within, EVT *which* tasks students invest in and *how much* cost they absorb. Together they predict that motivated learners engage regularly, exploratorily, timely, and resiliently—the behavioural signatures the MPI captures.")

